{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-topic-topic-tsx","path":"/topics/earwax/","result":{"data":{"firstChapter":{"id":"bb20b74f-ff4a-5289-a059-11984959944f","slug":"summary","fullItemName":"Summary","subChapters":[],"depth":1,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field fa5da18b-065b-4b55-a2af-2f36cdb8fae9 --><h1>Earwax: Summary</h1><!-- end field fa5da18b-065b-4b55-a2af-2f36cdb8fae9 -->","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item ea43cbf9-ec90-425d-a56e-da773fa432e8 --><!-- begin field 2087beca-2f21-4141-b331-c96e529c0706 --><ul><li>Earwax is a normal physiological substance which is a combination of dead flattened cells, cerumen (a wax-like substance), sebum, and various foreign substances (for example cosmetics and dirt).</li><li>Earwax cleans, lubricates, and protects the lining of the ear canal, trapping dirt and repelling water.</li><li>People are at risk of impacted earwax if they:<ul><li>Have narrow or deformed ear canals.</li><li>Have numerous hairs in their ear canals.</li><li>Have benign bony growths in the external auditory canal (osteomata).</li><li>Have a dermatological disease of the peri-auricular area or scalp.</li><li>Produce hard wax, as this is more likely to become impacted.</li><li>Are elderly (earwax tends to become drier in older people).</li><li>Have a history of recurrent impacted wax.</li><li>Have recurrent otitis externa.</li><li>Have Down's syndrome.</li></ul></li><li>The most common symptoms caused by impacted earwax are:<ul><li>Conductive hearing loss.</li><li>Blocked ears or a feeling of fullness in the ear.</li><li>Earache.</li><li>Tinnitus.</li><li>Itchiness.</li><li>Vertigo.</li></ul></li><li>Other conditions which should be excluded include:<ul><li>Otitis externa (inflammation of the auricle or external ear canal due to allergy, infection, or eczematous conditions).</li><li>Foreign bodies (particularly in children).</li></ul></li><li>Earwax should be removed if it is totally occluding the ear canal and:<ul><li>The person is symptomatic.</li><li>The tympanic membrane is obscured by wax but needs to be viewed to establish a diagnosis.</li><li>The person wears a hearing aid and an impression needs to be taken for a mould, or wax is causing the hearing aid to whistle.</li></ul></li><li>Initial management of earwax includes ear drops for 3–5 days initially, to soften wax.<ul><li>Sodium bicarbonate 5%, sodium chloride 0.9%, olive oil, or almond oil drops can be used.</li><li>Drops should not be prescribed if it is suspected that the person has a perforated tympanic membrane.</li></ul></li><li>If symptoms persist, ear irrigation can be considered, providing that there are no contraindications.</li><li>If irrigation is unsuccessful, there are three options:<ul><li>The use of ear drops for a further 3–5 days with a review for further irrigation.</li><li>Instillation of water into the ear and a repeat irrigation after 15 minutes.</li><li>Referral to an Ear, Nose, and Throat specialist for removal of wax.</li></ul></li><li>Anyone who has had earwax removed should be advised to return if they develop otalgia, itching, or discharge from the ear, or swelling of the external auditory meatus, as this may indicate infection.</li><li>Referral should be arranged to an Ear, Nose, and Throat specialist if the person has:<ul><li>A chronic perforation of the tympanic membrane.</li><li>A past history of ear surgery.</li><li>A foreign body in the ear canal.</li><li>Used ear drops, which have been unsuccessful, and irrigation is contraindicated.</li><li>Had unsuccessful irrigation.</li></ul></li><li>Advice should be urgently sought from an Ear, Nose, and Throat specialist if:<ul><li>Severe pain, deafness, or vertigo occur during or after irrigation, or if a perforation is seen following the procedure.</li><li>Infection is present and the external canal needs to be cleared of wax, debris, and discharge.</li></ul></li></ul><!-- end field 2087beca-2f21-4141-b331-c96e529c0706 --><!-- end item ea43cbf9-ec90-425d-a56e-da773fa432e8 -->","topic":{"id":"0860fbde-68cd-5672-ac9c-8ed2babea308","topicId":"04629b60-9cc0-4c9a-bf12-ad79b02112d0","topicName":"Earwax","slug":"earwax","aliases":[],"chapters":[{"id":"bb20b74f-ff4a-5289-a059-11984959944f","slug":"summary","fullItemName":"Summary","subChapters":[]},{"id":"3784d60a-d306-545e-afce-0b286e63aeea","slug":"have-i-got-the-right-topic","fullItemName":"Have I got the right topic?","subChapters":[]},{"id":"35138ccf-bf03-5e2d-a3b1-d0bd0553036c","slug":"how-up-to-date-is-this-topic","fullItemName":"How up-to-date is this topic?","subChapters":[{"id":"cf9919fb-08cb-55fd-9800-03d65dd6d6b4","slug":"changes","fullItemName":"Changes"},{"id":"b71aa620-0a5d-58cf-a6ef-8cbbbd3bb4d9","slug":"update","fullItemName":"Update"}]},{"id":"c12a90b5-b5ae-5f97-83e8-cff030bed13a","slug":"goals-outcome-measures","fullItemName":"Goals and outcome measures","subChapters":[{"id":"327a460e-5ddb-5f1d-8cc9-97049ca7a888","slug":"goals","fullItemName":"Goals"},{"id":"f2dbb076-a7b5-55e2-8fd0-465424b232cf","slug":"outcome-measures","fullItemName":"Outcome measures"},{"id":"2fd94a61-a283-56cb-8dd9-1489075d52e9","slug":"audit-criteria","fullItemName":"Audit criteria"},{"id":"aa6a62ac-4988-5e36-887e-23812f9a2db9","slug":"qof-indicators","fullItemName":"QOF indicators"},{"id":"52b5bb35-3773-5ac0-add1-dc397cff2d4a","slug":"qipp-options-for-local-implementation","fullItemName":"QIPP - Options for local implementation"},{"id":"0d6b67b8-543e-5883-b556-ac92241b0c5d","slug":"nice-quality-standards","fullItemName":"NICE Quality Standards"}]},{"id":"3df67c42-60bc-5fd9-a47d-d403cd8d088b","slug":"background-information","fullItemName":"Background information","subChapters":[{"id":"5ddf1e3b-bf77-5d33-a3d7-1091ec709c51","slug":"definition","fullItemName":"Definition"},{"id":"38a71348-a2c8-53c6-8388-e13ff4b91a32","slug":"risk-factors","fullItemName":"Risk factors"},{"id":"dafc860a-ff19-5e33-abc1-f20d4866d846","slug":"prevalence","fullItemName":"Prevalence"},{"id":"ae9c9959-effc-533d-93c1-4e1b3d1db89